text: Hypotonia cystinuria syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects infants and young children. It is caused by a deletion on the long (q) arm of chromosome 2, which leads to the absence of two important genes: SLC3A1 and PREPL. The absence of these genes can result in various symptoms such as weakness, poor growth, cystinuria (a condition where cystine is excreted in the urine), and nephrolithiasis (the formation of kidney stones). Additionally, some individuals with this disorder may also have minor facial dysmorphism. This syndrome is known as a chromosomal deletion syndrome, which occurs when there is a missing or extra piece of DNA in the genome that results in specific symptoms and characteristics.

Salmonellosis is a primary bacterial infectious disease caused by the bacteria of the genus Salmonella. Symptoms typically include diarrhea, fever, vomiting, and abdominal cramps 12 to 72 hours after infection. The illness lasts four to seven days on average, and most people recover without treatment.

Microphthalmia with limb anomalies is a type of autosomal recessive disease that is characterized by the bilateral or unilateral clinical anophthalmia or microphthalmia and synostosis, syndactyly, oligodactyly and/or polydactyly. It has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the SMOC1 gene on chromosome 14q24. It is also known by various other names such as MLA, OAS, Waardenburg anophthalmia syndrome, anophthalmia-syndactyly syndrome and ophthalmoacromelic syndrome.

Mal de Meleda is a type of palmoplantar keratosis, which is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of symmetric palmoplantar hyperkeratosis that progressively extends to the dorsal surfaces of hands and feet and ichthyotic changes elsewhere. It has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the SLURP1 gene on chromosome 8q24.
Mal de Meleda is also known as Meleda disease, palmoplantar keratoderma of Siemens, and transgrediens palmoplantar keratosis of Siemens.

patterned macular dystrophy is a type of macular degeneration characterized by abnormal accumulation of lipofuscin in the retinal pigment epithelium in a distinct pattern, which includes three patterns: reticular ('fishnet-like'), macroreticular ('spider-shaped'), and butterfly-shaped. It is also known as patterned dystrophy of retinal pigment epithelium.

Patterned macular dystrophy 2 (MDPT2) is a type of patterned macular dystrophy characterized by bilateral accumulation of pigmented or yellowish material at the level of the retinal pigment epithelium in lesions that resemble the wings of a butterfly. This condition has a genetic basis, specifically due to heterozygous mutation in the CTNNA1 gene on chromosome 5q31. MDPT2 is also known by its exact synonyms, "butterfly-shaped pigmentary maculary dystrophy 2" and "MDPT2."

Patterned macular dystrophy 3, also known as Martinique crinkled retinal pigment epitheliopathy, is a type of patterned macular dystrophy characterized by the 'dry desert land' pattern of the fundus, involving the posterior pole initially and progressing from the temporal fovea to the periphery of the retina developing in the fourth or fifth decade of life. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the MAPKAPK3 gene on chromosome 3p21. This condition is also known by its exact synonym, MDPT3.

Patterned macular dystrophy type 1 is a type of Patterned macular dystrophy, characterized by the accumulation of pigmented or yellowish material at the level of the retinal pigment epithelium in lesions that resemble the wings of a butterfly. This condition is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the PRPH2 gene on chromosome 6p21. It has been referred to as MDPT1 and butterfly-shaped pigmentary maculary dystrophy type 1.

Macrocephaly autism syndrome is a condition that is characterized by an enlarged head, a square facial outline with frontal bossing, midface retrusion, and other facial characteristics. It also has developmental delay and autism as part of its symptoms. The exact cause of this condition is not fully understood, but it can be inherited in some cases, and mutations in the PTEN gene on chromosome 10q23 are known to have a material basis in this syndrome.

Leukoencephalopathy with vanishing white matter is a rare genetic disorder that affects the brain. It causes progressive damage to the white matter of the brain, which can lead to symptoms such as ataxia (loss of coordination), spasticity (muscle stiffness and rigidity), and cognitive impairment. The condition is often diagnosed in childhood and may continue into adulthood. It has a specific set of clinical features that help doctors make an accurate diagnosis.

Late-onset retinal degeneration (LORD) is a type of retinal degeneration that affects people in their late 40s to 6th decade. It is characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance, which means that it can be passed down through generations in families. LORD typically starts with night blindness and the accumulation of drusen deposits on the retina. As the disease progresses, it causes severe central and peripheral degeneration, leading to choroidal neovascularization and chorioretinal atrophy. The underlying cause of LORD is a mutation in the C1QTNF5 gene located on chromosome 11q23.

Isolated growth hormone deficiency (IGHD) is a type of hypopituitarism characterized by abnormally low levels, absence or impaired function of growth hormone in the absence of abnormalities in other pituitary hormones. It is also known as congenital IGHD, familial isolated GH deficiency, and non-acquired isolated growth hormone deficiency.

Autosomal dominant keratitis ichthyosis deafness syndrome, also known as KID syndrome, is a genetic disorder characterized by congenital deafness, keratopachydermia, and constrictions of fingers and toes. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the GJB2 gene on chromosome 13q.

Isolated growth hormone deficiency type II, also known as IGHD II or autosomal dominant isolated growth hormone deficiency, is a condition characterized by low but detectable levels of GH1 resulting in variable degrees of dwarfism that are responsive to growth hormone therapy. This type of growth hormone deficiency is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner and is due to dominant negative mutations in the GH1 gene located on chromosome 17q23.3. Other synonyms for this condition include congenital IGHD type II, congenital isolated GH deficiency type II, and congenital isolated growth hormone deficiency type II.

Isolated growth hormone deficiency type IA, also known as IGHD-IA, is a form of isolated growth hormone deficiency characterized by severe dwarfism that begins before 6 months of age and the presence of antibodies to growth hormone following exogenous supplementation. This condition is caused by mutations in the GH1 gene on chromosome 17q23.3. It has exact synonyms such as IGHD-IA, Illig-type growth hormone deficiency, autosomal recessive isolated growth hormone deficiency, pituitary dwarfism I, primordial dwarfism, and sexual ateleiotic dwarfism.

Isolated growth hormone deficiency type IB (IGHD-IB) is a rare form of isolated growth hormone deficiency characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of low but detectable levels of GH, short stature, significantly retarded bone age, and a positive response and immunologic tolerance to growth hormone therapy. It is caused by mutations in the GH1 or GHRHR genes on chromosomes 17q23.3 and 7p14.3, respectively. It has exact synonyms such as congenital IGHD type IB, congenital isolated GH deficiency type IB, dwarfism of Sindh, and has an OMIM code of 618157.

Isolated growth hormone deficiency type III is a rare genetic disorder characterized by dwarfism, variable occurrence of hypogammaglobulinemia, and a generally good response to growth hormone therapy. It has material basis in mutations in the BTK gene on chromosome Xq22.1. This condition is also known as Fleisher syndrome, IGHD III, X-linked IGHD, X-linked agammaglobulinemia and isolated growth hormone deficiency, X-linked hypogammaglobulinemia and isolated growth hormone deficiency, X-linked isolated growth hormone deficiency, congenital IGHD type III, congenital isolated GH deficiency type III, and congenital isolated growth hormone deficiency type III. It is also known as growth hormone deficiency with hypogammaglobulinemia.

Bullous congenital ichthyosiform erythroderma is a type of autosomal dominant disease, characterized by the presence of multiple skin blisters on the body. These blisters can develop into gray hyperkeratoses with a lichenified appearance, and are associated with congenital erythema (redness). The condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutations in the KRT2 gene on chromosome 12q13. It is also known by other names such as bullous type ichthyosis, ichthyosis bullosa of Siemens, and superficial epidermolytic ichthyosis.

Hypoparathyroidism, deafness, and renal disease syndrome (HDRS) is a rare genetic disorder characterized by the presence of three main features: hypoparathyroidism, sensorineural deafness, and progressive renal disease. HDRS is caused by a deletion on chromosome 10p14 which results in haploinsufficiency of the GATA3 gene. The disorder has autosomal dominant inheritance and typically presents in childhood or adolescence. It is also known as Barakat syndrome, HDR syndrome, and hypoparathyroidism, sensorineural deafness, and renal disease (HSDR).

Primary hypomagnesemia is a metabolic disorder characterized by low levels of magnesium in the blood. It typically affects infants and children, and can lead to symptoms such as muscle weakness, seizures, and abnormal heart rhythms. In some cases, it may be caused by genetic factors or other underlying health conditions. Treatment typically involves supplementing the individual with magnesium and addressing any underlying health issues.

Renal hypomagnesemia 3 is a type of primary hypomagnesemia, which is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of excessive urinary Ca(2+) and Mg(2+) excretion that has material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CLDN16 gene on chromosome 3q28. It has exact synonyms such as FHHNC without severe ocular involvement, HOMG3, familial primary hypomagnesemia with hypercalciuria and nephrocalcinosis without severe ocular involvement, isolated renal hypomagnesemia, and primary hypomagnesemia due to defect in renal tubular transport of magnesium. It is also known as renal hypomagnesemia type 3.

Renal hypomagnesemia 5 with ocular involvement is a type of primary hypomagnesemia characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of renal magnesium wasting with hypercalcinosis, progressive renal failure and severe ocular involvement. This condition has material basis in homozygous mutation in the CLDN19 gene on chromosome 1p34.2. Exact synonyms for this condition include FHHNC with severe ocular involvement, Meier-Blumberg-Imahorn syndrome, bilateral macular coloboma with hypercalciuria, familial hypomagnesemia with hypercalciuria, nephrocalcinosis and severe ocular involvement, and hypercalciuria-bilateral macular coloboma syndrome.

Renal hypomagnesemia type 4, also known as HOMG4, is a condition characterized by isolated hypomagnesemia due to renal loss with normal serum calcium levels and urinary calcium excretion. It has a genetic basis and is linked to a variation in the chromosome region 4q25.<|endoftext|>

Renal hypomagnesemia type 6, also known as HOMG6, is a form of primary hypomagnesemia. It is characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance of severely lowered serum magnesium levels without other electrolyte disturbances or abnormalities in urinary magnesium excretion that are due to heterozygous mutations in the CNNM2 gene on chromosome 10q24.

Renal hypomagnesemia type 2, also known as HOMG2, is a form of primary hypomagnesemia characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance. This means that the condition is passed down through generations within a family and can be caused by a mutation in the FXYD2 gene on chromosome 11q23.

Osteopathia striata with cranial sclerosis is a rare genetic disorder characterized by the abnormal development of bone tissue in the skull, leading to thickening and hardening (sclerosis) of certain areas. This condition is also known as Robinow-Unger syndrome or hyperostosis generalisata with striations. It affects both males and females but can result in severe complications such as cleft palate, hearing loss, and skull deformities during fetal development, which can cause stillbirth in males. In some cases, affected individuals may have an enlarged head (macrocephaly) or other skeletal abnormalities. The disorder is caused by mutations in the AMER1 gene located on the X chromosome.

Ossification of the posterior longitudinal ligament (OPLL) is a connective tissue disease that affects the spine. It occurs when there is ectopic ossification, or growth of bone in an abnormal location, specifically along the posterior longitudinal ligament which runs down the center of the spinal column. This can lead to compression of the spinal cord and surrounding nerves, causing symptoms such as pain, weakness, and reflex changes. OPLL is more common in people over 50 years old and can also occur in younger individuals, particularly those with certain genetic predispositions or medical conditions that affect connective tissue health. Treatment options for OPLL include non-surgical approaches such as medications to reduce inflammation or pain, or surgical interventions like decompression or fusion of the affected vertebrae.

Transient Myeloproliferative Syndrome (TMPS) is a type of Transient Myeloproliferative Neoplasm (TMN). TMNs are characterized by the overproduction of white blood cells in newborns with Down syndrome. The exact synonyms for TMPS include MST, TAM, and transient abnormal myelopoiesis. It can also be referred to as transient leukemia or transient leukemia of Down syndrome, but it is not technically considered a type of cancer. Instead, it is a condition where the body produces too many white blood cells, which can lead to anemia and other health issues if left untreated.

prune belly syndrome is a rare genetic disorder characterized by the weakness of abdominal muscles, which can lead to a hollow or sunken appearance of the abdomen. It typically affects boys and men and has a homozygous mutation in the CHRM3 gene on chromosome 1q43. Other symptoms may include cryptorchidism (undescended testicles), megacystis (large, fluid-filled cysts in the kidneys), and thin or absent abdominal muscles. It is also known as Eagle-Barrett syndrome, Obriskysy syndrome, and abdominal muscle deficiency syndrome.

Ectopic Cushing syndrome, also known as Cushing Syndrome due to ectopic ACTH secretion or Ectopic ACTH secreting tumor, is a type of primary hyperaldosteronism. It occurs when a tumor outside the pituitary gland produces Adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH), which causes the adrenal glands to produce excessive cortisol. This leads to the symptoms associated with Cushing syndrome, such as weight gain, fatigue, and increased blood sugar levels. Ectopic Cushing syndrome is a rare condition that can be difficult to diagnose and treat. It requires a specialized team of doctors and appropriate testing to make an accurate diagnosis and develop an effective treatment plan.

Late-onset Parkinson's disease (LOPD) is a type of Parkinson's disease that occurs later in life, typically after the age of 60. It is characterized by motor symptoms such as tremors, rigidity, and slowness of movement. The exact synonym for LOPD is late-onset Parkinson disease.

juvenile onset parkinson's disease has exact synonym juvenile-onset Parkinson's disease.

Early onset Parkinson's disease is a type of Parkinson's disease that presents with motor symptoms before the age of 50. This condition shares many of the same characteristics as other types of Parkinson's disease, including progressive loss of dopamine-producing neurons in the substantia nigra region of the brain. However, it often has a more aggressive course and may respond differently to treatment. It is also more likely to be inherited or have a genetic component.

Parkinson's disease 4, also known as autosomal dominant Lewy body Parkinson disease 4 or autosomal dominant Parkinson disease 4, is a type of late-onset Parkinson's disease. It is characterized by the presence of Lewy bodies in the brain, which are abnormal aggregations of protein that can cause neurological symptoms such as tremors, rigidity, and difficulty with movement. This form of Parkinson's disease is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that a single copy of the gene is sufficient to increase the risk of developing the disease. The exact synonym for this condition is Parkinson's disease 4, which has a material basis in heterozygous triplication of the alpha-synuclein gene on chromosome 4q22.

Parkinson's disease (PD) is a neurological disorder that affects movement. It belongs to a group of conditions called motor neuron diseases, which are characterized by the degeneration of motor neurons in the brain and spinal cord. PD can cause a range of symptoms, including tremors, stiffness, and difficulty with balance and coordination.
PD is caused by the loss of dopamine-producing cells in the brain, which leads to a decrease in the neurotransmitter dopamine. There are various theories about what causes the loss of these cells, but it's likely that a combination of genetic and environmental factors play a role.
There are several types of PD, including early-onset and late-onset forms. Early-onset PD typically begins before age 50, while late-onset PD develops after age 65. Some people may also experience atypical PD symptoms that do not fit into either category, such as depression or anxiety without physical symptoms.
Treatment for PD can include medications to manage symptoms, surgery to alleviate motor issues, and physical therapy to improve mobility and balance.

Parkinson's disease 17 (PD17) is a type of Parkinson's disease that has a genetic component and can be passed down through families. It typically develops later in life, although some people may experience symptoms earlier. PD17 results from mutations in the VPS35 gene on chromosome 16q13. This type of Parkinson's disease is known as autosomal dominant, meaning that only one copy of the faulty gene is needed to develop the condition.

Parkinson's disease is a neurological disorder that affects movement. It is caused by the degeneration of dopamine-producing neurons in the brain. The exact cause of the disease is not yet fully understood, but it is thought to be a combination of genetic and environmental factors.
Parkinson's disease typically develops slowly over time, with symptoms such as tremors, rigidity, and difficulty moving. In some cases, it can also affect a person's speech, mood, and cognitive abilities.
There are several types of Parkinson's disease, including early-onset and late-onset forms. Early-onset Parkinson's disease typically begins before the age of 50, while late-onset Parkinson's disease develops after the age of 60.
Treatment for Parkinson's disease may include medications to manage symptoms, surgical interventions, and physical therapy. It is important for individuals with Parkinson's disease to work closely with their healthcare providers to develop a personalized treatment plan that addresses their specific needs and preferences.

Parkinson's disease 14, also known as late-onset Parkinson's disease, is a type of autosomal recessive disorder that is characterized by the gradual loss of motor skills and physical coordination. It is caused by mutations in the PLA2G6 gene located on chromosome 22q13. This form of Parkinson's disease typically appears later in life, often after the age of 50, and affects both men and women equally.

In addition to motor symptoms such as tremors, stiffness, and difficulty with balance and coordination, people with Parkinson's disease 14 may also experience non-motor symptoms such as cognitive decline, sleep disturbances, and emotional changes. Early detection and proper treatment can help manage the symptoms of this condition and improve quality of life.

Lymphoplasmacytic lymphoma, also known as Waldenstrom's macroglobulinemia, is a type of B-cell lymphoma characterized by the accumulation of monoclonal cells in the bone marrow and peripheral lymphoid tissues, and associated with the production of serum immunoglobulin M (IgM) monoclonal protein. It is also known as lymphoplasmacytic lymphoma with IgM gammopathy.

Norman-Roberts syndrome is a type of lissencephaly that has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the gene encoding reelin (RELN) on chromosome 7q22. It is an autosomal recessive disease, which means that it requires the presence of two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) for the syndrome to develop. Lissencephaly is a congenital brain malformation characterized by the absence or hypoplasia of cerebral white matter. It can result in a range of neurological symptoms, including developmental delay, seizures, and motor skill impairments. Norman-Roberts syndrome is also known as lissencephaly 2 and lissencephaly syndrome, Norman-Roberts type.

Thrombosis is a type of vascular disease that occurs when a blood clot forms inside a blood vessel, causing it to become blocked and impeding the flow of blood through the circulatory system. This can lead to various health problems, including heart attacks, stroke, and gangrene. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect you may be experiencing symptoms of thrombosis, as prompt treatment can help prevent serious complications.

Legume allergy is not the same as a fruit allergy. It is an allergy to legumes, which are a type of plant that belongs to the Fabaceae family. This can include things like beans, peas, and lentils. The allergen in these foods is typically one of several proteins found in them, such as lectin or vicilin. Some common symptoms of legume allergy may include itching or swelling of the mouth, throat tightness, difficulty breathing, and even anaphylaxis in severe cases. It is important to avoid legumes if you have this allergy, and to read ingredient lists carefully for any hidden sources of legumes in food products.

Karyomegalic interstitial nephritis is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the kidneys. It is characterized by inflammation, scarring, and enlarged nuclei in the tubular epithelial cells. The condition has a material basis in mutations in the FAN1 gene on chromosome 15q13.3.

CRANIOSYNOSTOSIS 7 (CRS7) is a type of craniosynostosis, which is characterized by the premature fusion of skull bones. It is caused by a weakly penetrant heterozygous mutation in the SMAD6 gene on chromosome 15q22. The risk allele for this condition is typically found near the BMP2 gene on chromosome 20p12.

CRS7 can result in intracranial pressure elevation, which may lead to further complications if left untreated. Treatment options for CRS7 include surgery and monitoring of intracranial pressure. Early diagnosis and treatment are essential for managing the symptoms and improving outcomes for individuals with this condition.

Proteosome-Associated Autoinflammatory Syndrome (PAPS) is a rare genetic disorder that affects multiple body systems. It is characterized by recurrent fever, joint contractures, lipodystrophy, hepatosplenomegaly, anemia, and calcifications. These symptoms typically begin in early childhood and can be severe and debilitating.
PAPS is caused by mutations in the proteosome genes and leads to dysregulation of the immune response, which results in chronic inflammation. The disorder can also affect other body systems such as skin, bones, and joints. Treatment for PAPS typically involves managing symptoms with medications and providing supportive care.
It is important to note that while rare, PAPS can be a serious and life-altering condition. If you or someone you know is experiencing symptoms of PAPS, it is crucial to seek medical attention immediately.

Yes, Proteosome Associated Autoinflammatory Syndrome 2 (PRAAS2) is a type of autosomal dominant disease that is characterized by severe inflammatory neutrophilic dermatitis, autoimmunity, and variable immunodeficiency. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the POMP gene on chromosome 13q12. The condition is also known as Proteasome-Associated Autoinflammatory Syndrome 2 (PRAAS2).

Proteosome associated autoinflammatory syndrome 4, also known as PRAAS4, is a rare autosomal recessive disorder that typically presents in early infancy with symptoms such as panniculitis and erythematous skin lesions. The condition may also involve lymphadenopathy, myositis, delayed motor and speech development, and autoimmune features. It has a genetic basis, with mutations in the PSMG2 gene on chromosome 18p11 being responsible for the disease.

Facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy 3 is a type of facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy characterized by adult onset of proximal muscle weakness affecting the face, neck, scapular muscles, and upper and lower limbs that has_material_basis_in the combination of a homozygous mutation in the LRIF1 gene on chromosome 1p13 and presence of a haplotype on chromosome 4 that is permissive for DUX4 expression. It has the exact synonym FSHD3, and facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy type 3.

Facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy 4 (FSHD4) is a type of facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy. It is characterized by the adult onset of progressive muscle weakness in the face and upper extremity muscles, with disease progression that has a material basis in the combination of a heterozygous mutation in the DNMT3B gene on chromosome 20q11 and presence of a haplotype on chromosome 4 that is permissive for DUX4 expression. It has the exact synonyms FSHD4 and facioscapulohumeral muscular dystrophy type 4.

otosclerosis 1 is a type of otosclerosis. It is characterized by isolated endochondral bone sclerosis of the labyrinthine capsule, and it has material basis in the locus associated with the OTSC1 gene on chromosome 15q26.1. It also has an exact synonym, which is OTSC1.

otosclerosis 2 is a form of otosclerosis, which is a medical condition characterized by the growth of bone in the middle ear. It is caused by genetic factors and can lead to hearing loss if left untreated. Otosclerosis 2 specifically refers to a type of otosclerosis that is associated with a gene on chromosome 7q, specifically the locus associated with the OTSC2 gene. It is important to be aware of this condition and seek medical attention if you suspect you may have it.
Otosclerosis 3 is a specific type of otosclerosis that has a genetic basis, specifically on the chromosome 6p. This type of otosclerosis is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner.

Otosclerosis 4, also known as OTSC4, is a type of otosclerosis that has a genetic basis and is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner. It is caused by mutations in the OTSC4 gene, which is located on chromosome 16q. This condition can cause hearing loss and other complications if left untreated.

Otosclerosis 5 is a specific type of otosclerosis that is characterized by conductive hearing impairment and has a genetic basis. It is associated with the locus on chromosome 3, specifically between q22-q24, which is linked to the OTSC5 gene. The OTSC5 gene is involved in the development of otosclerosis, a condition where abnormal bone growth occurs within the inner ear and causes hearing loss. This specific type of otosclerosis affects both males and females and can be inherited from an affected parent.

Otosclerosis 7, also known as OTSC7, is a type of otosclerosis that has a genetic basis. It is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that if one parent has the gene, there is a 50% chance that their child will inherit it. The locus associated with the OTSC7 gene is located on chromosome 6q13.

otosclerosis 8, also known as OTSC8, is a type of otosclerosis that has a material basis in the locus associated with the otosclerosis-8 gene on chromosome 9p13.1-q21.11. It is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner.

Otosclerosis 10, also known as OTSC10, is a subtype of otosclerosis characterized by the presence of a genetic mutation on chromosome 1q41-q44. This specific form of the disease has a strong familial predisposition and can cause conductive hearing loss due to the abnormal growth of bone in the middle ear. It is important for individuals with a family history of otosclerosis to seek genetic counseling and regular check-ups with an ENT specialist to monitor their hearing health and identify any potential issues early on.

otosclerosis 11 is a form of otosclerosis, which is characterized by progressive hearing loss that typically begins in the second to third decade of life. It has a genetic basis and is linked to the locus associated with the Forkhead Box L1 gene (FOXL1) on chromosome 16q24. The exact synonym for otosclerosis 11 is OTSC11.

non syndromic x linked intellectual developmental disorder 111 is a type of non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability that is characterized by different degrees of impaired intellectual development associated with motor, speech and behavioral impairments. It has a material basis in hemizygous or heterozygous mutation in the SLITRK2 gene on chromosome Xq27. It has the exact synonym XLID111.

Developmental dysplasia of the hip is a type of bone development disease that affects the hip joint. It occurs when the ball at the end of the thighbone (femoral head) does not sit properly in the socket (acetabulum) of the pelvis. This can cause abnormalities in the growth and development of the hips, leading to a range of issues such as limping, difficulty walking, and arthritis. It is important for individuals with this condition to receive appropriate treatment and care to ensure proper bone and joint development.

developmental dysplasia of the hip 1 is a genetic condition that affects the development of the hip joint. It occurs when there is a problem with the formation of the hip socket, which can cause the ball of the hip joint to be shallow. This condition can lead to problems with walking and running, and may also increase the risk of arthritis in later life. Developmental dysplasia of the hip 1 can be inherited as an autosomal dominant trait, meaning that if one parent has the gene for the condition, there is a 50% chance that their child will inherit it. It is also sometimes referred to as DDH1, and can have a material basis in variation in the chromosomal region 13q22.

Developmental dysplasia of the hip 2 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which means that it can be passed down through families and tends to affect multiple family members. The condition is characterized by incomplete formation of the acetabulum leading to dislocation of the femur, suboptimal joint function, and accelerated wear of the articular cartilage, resulting in arthritis. It has a material basis in variation in the chromosomal region 3p22.2., which is why it is sometimes referred to as DDH2.

3 methylglutaconic aciduria type 8 is a rare genetic disorder caused by mutations in the HTRA2 gene. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that to develop the condition, a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene, one from each parent. The disorder affects the body's ability to break down 3-methylglutaconic acid, leading to the accumulation of this substance in various tissues and organs. This can cause a range of symptoms, including neurological problems, developmental delays, and muscle weakness. Treatment may involve dietary restrictions, medications, and other supportive measures to manage symptoms and improve quality of life.

Post-Cardiac Arrest Syndrome (PCAS) is a complex clinical entity that occurs following cardiac arrest. The management of PCAS involves addressing the underlying cause, providing appropriate supportive care, and implementing evidence-based interventions for each component of the syndrome.

Nevus syndrome, also known as nevoid basal cell carcinoma syndrome (NBCCS), is a rare genetic disorder that affects the skin and other organs. It is characterized by the presence of multiple benign tumors called nevus (mole) or basal cell carcinoma (BCC). NBCCS is caused by mutations in the SUFU gene, which is located on chromosome 10q24. The syndrome has been renamed to Basal Cell Nevus Syndrome 2 (BCNS2), but it is still commonly referred to as NBCCS.

There are several types of NBCCS, and they are usually classified based on the age of onset and the severity of the disease. The most severe form of the syndrome is known as Gorlin-Goltz Syndrome, which typically presents in childhood with multiple large, jawbone tumors called odontogenic keratocysts (OKC), along with numerous BCCs.

Symptoms of NBCCS may include:
1. Multiple benign skin growths (nevi or moles) that can turn into cancer over time if not treated
2. Multiple basal cell carcinomas (BCCs) on the face and scalp, which are slow-growing but can become aggressive if left untreated
3. Odontogenic keratocysts (OKCs) in severe cases
4. Skin pitting or scarring from BCC surgery
5. Multiple jawbone tumors (odontogenic keratocysts, OKCs), particularly in the severe form of the syndrome called Gorlin-Goltz Syndrome

Treatment for NBCCS usually involves monitoring and removal of the growths by a dermatologist or plastic surgeon. Preventive measures like sunscreen use are also recommended to reduce the risk of BCC development. In severe cases, such as Gorlin-Goltz Syndrome, more extensive treatment may be necessary, including radiation therapy, chemotherapy, or surgical removal of affected tissues and organs.

In summary, nevoid basal cell carcinoma syndrome (NBCCS) is a rare genetic disorder that can cause multiple benign skin growths and other health issues if left untreated. Early detection and proper treatment are essential to prevent complications and maintain a good quality of life.

text: north carolina macular dystrophy is a type of retinal macular dystrophy that is characterized by limited drusen, larger confluent drusen, or severe colobomatous-like chorioretinal atrophy in the central macular region present at birth that are nonprogressive and have a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in a DNase I hypersensitivity site on chromosome 6q16 upstream of the PRDM13 gene. It has exact synonyms such as central areolar pigment epithelial dystrophy, central retinal pigment epithelial dystrophy, progressive foveal dystrophy, and retinal macular dystrophy 1. It also has an exact match in the OMIM database with UMLS_CUI:C0730294.

Retinal macular dystrophy 3, also known as MCDR3, is a type of retinal macular dystrophy that has a genetic basis in variation within the chromosomal region 5p15.33-p13.1. It is characterized by degeneration of the macula, which can lead to vision loss and blindness if left untreated. This condition is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that a person has an 50% chance of inheriting it from a affected parent. There is no cure for MCDR3, but treatments such as low vision aids, glasses, and genetic counseling can help manage the symptoms.

Retinal macular dystrophy 4, also known as MCDR4 or OMIM:619977, is a type of retinal macular dystrophy characterized by late-onset macular degeneration. It is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the CLEC3B gene on chromosome 3p21. The condition is marked by multiple drusen-like deposits, macular geographic atrophy, and choroidal neovascularization.

Paroxysmal nonkinesigenic dyskinesia 3 (PND3) is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects movement. It causes sudden and involuntary movements called dystonia, which can be accompanied by epilepsy or other neurological symptoms. The condition has a material basis in mutations in the KCNMA1 gene on chromosome 10q22. PND3 can be diagnosed with a physical examination and genetic testing, and treatment may involve medications to control seizures and dystonia. It is important for individuals with this condition to work closely with their healthcare provider to manage their symptoms effectively.

neurodevelopmental disorder with cerebellar atrophy and motor dysfunction is a type of autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder. It is characterized by cerebellar atrophy and global developmental delay with cognitive impairment, speech delay, and prominent motor abnormalities including axial hypotonia, gait ataxia, and appendicular spasticity that has_material_basis_in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GEMIN5 gene on chromosome 5q33.2. It is also known as OMIM:619333.

Early onset dystonia and or spastic paraplegia, also known as hereditary motor neurographia with spasticity, is a type of autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by the presence of dystonia, spasticity or both, which has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the ATP5MC3 gene on chromosome 2q31.1. Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 16, also known as mtDNA deletion syndrome or mtDNA depletion syndrome with hepatic involvement, is a rare genetic disorder that affects mitochondria. It is caused by the deletion of a large portion of mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA), which leads to a decrease in the production of adenosine triphosphate (ATP). This energy deficiency can result in multiple organ systems being affected, including the liver, brain, and eyes.

The symptoms of mtDNA depletion syndrome 16 typically begin in early infancy and can include poor feeding, vomiting, lethargy, failure to thrive, seizures, and developmental delay. The disease is usually fatal within a few years of onset, although some cases have been reported with milder symptoms.

Diagnosis of mtDNA depletion syndrome 16 typically involves a combination of clinical examination, genetic testing, and measurement of DNA levels in blood cells. Treatment options are limited and primarily focus on managing symptoms and providing supportive care. However, research is ongoing to better understand this disorder and develop effective treatments.

In conclusion, mtDNA depletion syndrome 16 is a genetic disorder that affects mitochondria and can cause severe health problems due to energy deficiency. While there is no cure for the disease, early diagnosis and supportive care can help improve quality of life for affected individuals.
